<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Brugge, Belgium: 02/08/2003<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.88)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10885'>Wouter "Venator" Neyt</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10885&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 15, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> De Striep, Brugge, Belgium: 02/08/2003<br />
<br />
De Striep is my local gamer shop where we try to do tournaments on a monthly base. We are doing a kind of competition: who scores the best at the end of the year, gets a small statue of Arwen. After this second tournament that counts for it, I am still second in the run for it (10 won of 12). My two lost matches were against Luc van Compernolle (1816), who has won all his match-ups. He’s a great player, that’s his main strength, but personally, I think I am a bit of a better deck builder.<br />
<br />
I think it was a great and interesting tournament, more interesting than the first one, where I had only two interesting match-ups. Now, at least five of my matches were a challenge. Five good decks and three good players, it was a very pleasant day. There were ca. 20 players.<br />
<br />
I start with 1679 rating and play a deck based on frodo signet and Mind your own affairs. I focus around Gandalf and Aragorn playing two servants, two bows, a shadowfax, a rangers sword and two brands. I posted it but already made a lot of changes. Oh yeah, minions were Moria with three cave trolls. Not all my memories are clear, so mistakes are always possible.<br />
<br />
First opponent: Tony de Vos (1590)<br />
<br />
He first tells me that he had a party the day before and had to puke this morning at 4.00 AM.<br />
We are now 11.00 AM. He indeed looks very ill. It’s obvious he has a heavy hangover. He isn’t too self-confident. First impression: an easy victory, but it turned out to be a weird game.<br />
Mostly in my environment, they bid one. I bid two: it turns out he had the same plan. I lose my dice roll, and he starts. Not with The Riddermark like I hoped, but with the East Wall. Oh boy, I draw six minion cards. But I have two armories and a swarm, so I don’t choose to mulligan. He moves to three and I clear my hand but I get nothing on my swarms, because he plays ringbound rangers. When I reconcile for the second time, I still haven’t seen a new companion, so it’s only legolas, gimli and frodo and two free pool. I play the wold of rohan myself, so man, am I facing a lot of pool. He plays an uruk of the new set with 12 strength, and plays a broad-bladed sword on it plus a saruman’s ambition. I am forced to exhaust legolas and gimli. (gimli makes legolas 10 and he takes two wounds). If I move, I have two dead companions. Knowing I will also have to stop on the sanctuary, my free peoples are not doing great. He moves to four, with still only his starting companions (probably he is having the same problem as me). With a guard commander and a scavenger, I manage to win some skirmishes and do some wounds. He is playing denial, so I am keeping my runner in my hand and hope to draw a scimitar, so I can play my cave-troll. I draw Aragorn and a Sting. Site three is my golden hall, so I am sacrificing one of my two stings to see his hand: no paths, no stealths. He plays one card but doesn’t discard one while reconciling. So if I can, Frodo will be a target for a swarm. I draw another runner and a host of thousands. He plays a sword on faramir and moves. I play my two runners, go fetch a scavengers and a scimitar (giving me two pool) and with the 10 pool left, I play a troll. I am putting my hand in the direction of armories to cancel Help in doubt and need, but he doesn’t even bother. He sees it’s over and shakes my hand. I don’t know if he had a bad draw or if he hoped only playing three companions, would be heavy denial. The boy is obviously in pain, so I decide to leave the table and go talk to a friend of mine, who has a bye.<br />
<br />
Second game: Niek Vanderispaillie (1623)<br />
Same scenario, we bid the same number of burdens and he gets a start with a non-riddermark site. He plays faramir and merry, it’s an elven ally deck that plays lasts alliances on faramir. He plays a legolas, no weapons, he suspects a golden hall or he didn’t drew any. I play an armory and a swarms, and clear my hand. Now I am able to play aragorn and merry from my hand, planning to sac merry on the way to three, so I have four companions. But it turns out saccing my gimli is a better plan, so I can save my merry for when I want to win against a troop of uruk-hai. Not having drawn my gandalf, I decide it’s not worth it to keep my shadowfax in my hand. I reconcile and draw my gandalf, typical. He plays galadriel and some free elven allies. I play a nertea and some minions that will get on my swarms. But he plays a secret sentinels, gosh darnit. The nertea stays in game so I discard one and reconcile. A new swarms and a new armory. He moves and thanks to a few scimitars, I have two minions on my swarms now. I decide risking a few savageries and plan to let gandalf replace merry. He plays two savageries and I have to stop. He goes to six, letting me play a cheap cave-troll who lets my other minions win, because faramir and aragorn are the only one not overwhelmed. If he had played the last alliance not on aragorn but on faramir, my dark places would have been a problem. I think legolas died, because he tried to shoot some minions, but I prevented the wounds with my armories. Most important, he hasn’t played a sentinels. Now I have a possible kill on site 7, if he doesn’t play a bow. I decide to make not too much pool and throw the costly things away, play a narya and a brand. I stop at 5. He only draws two new cards. He plays a sword, a last alliance and an armor. The cave troll is obviously bothering him. Perhaps that is the reason why he doesn’t use his sting leaving two vitality on frodo for filibert. Or maybe one pool isn’t enough for using his sting. Either way, because he can’t do wounds during maneuver or archery, my site 7 is lethal as I play 5 minions for 4 companions, who have all at least 6 strength. If we look at what the outcome would have been, if I didn’t took the guess that he wouldn’t draw much new cards and tried to move to 6, he would have drawn a rumil. This one sure was a close match and very exciting.<br />
<br />
Third opponent: Jonathan De Mey (first tournament)<br />
<br />
Not a third time, so I bid three. I don’t like counting on my minions. He bids zero. I turn my eyes to heaven. Very weird day. Replacing gimli with sam, I start. Having a weird opening hand, I play 4 companions. I say I want to test his shadow side, he only plays two minions. There is still 8 pool. He plays the uncommon uruk-hai of the first set: the ragers and the slayers. I suspect he isn’t playing too many rare cards, so I decide to only sac sam. I go to three. I go to five. I go to six. I go to eight. I can’t remember what my minions has done more than heavy cycling trough my deck, as he has managed to keep up with me. He’s a slow player and the tournament director is a bit worried that we will run out of time. Still having two minutes, I show him if my opponent goes for the tie win by also moving to site 8, he faces certain death. I just have to say I will go to 9. Seeing that stalling won’t work, he stops at seven. I move to 9, with a servant in my hand and two paths. Turns out I don’t even need them. I hear I am only one of three with three wins. The other guys are Luc van Compernolle and Lander Oosterlynck, a friend of mine. I hope I get the match against some dude with two victories, as I played the whole 45 minutes for the first time and I am a bit tired. Irony again, I have to play directly against Luc.<br />
<br />
The clash of titans<br />
<br />
I know it’s possible to win and he knows he will have to play on his highest level. I am sitting next to my friend Lander, I wish I had his opponent who has made a fun deck. I accept that eventually this would come, so I try to be very concentrated. I bid three, just like him. I win the roll and I start. I keep gimli, cause I know he isn’t playing on burdens. I get a decent, average free peoples hand with gandalf and aragorn. He thinks a lot and plays not too much minions for the pool he has, I hope it’s bluff, and that he had a bad draw. He can move to three. I have a bad minion hand, not too spectacular. I move to four, there is seven pool, he plays a troop, I have a strength 10 gandalf, a servant and two affairs in my hand. The plan is to only play one affair and exhaust legolas, so the troop is gone. But he plays a savagery and I play my other affairs, so if he has more pump-up, he has to keep it in his hand. I count eleven pool, two uruk-hai (three if he is lucky) and a saruman. I think I can handle that. But if he didn’t drew bad, I am dead. I look at my minions, and decide I want the servant and affairs out of my hand, otherwise he moves to 5 too easy. So I move and I face 5 uruk-hai and saruman. It’s over. The tournament director says to me that I shouldn’t have moved. Luc is disappointed, that I took such a risk. I explain how I saw it, but I can’t hide my disappointment either. Would I have won, if I played “normally”? I plan to do some research on how uruk decks exactly work, as they’re not my best match-up possible and that’s the fourth one I saw today. Luckily it’s also my last one. My friend has won, he now is facing Luc. I give him some hints, but I don’t think it will be much help.<br />
<br />
Five: Hans Vandendriesche (first tournament)<br />
<br />
Never seen this guy before and during the afternoon break, I had a little chat with him. He told me was playing easterlings. With 4 affairs and 2 paths I will have to take care for the burdens. I bid three (against his one) and start sam and legolas. Because I am interested in playing the raider culture, I did some research, so I know their weak points. You have to exhaust the burden-adders with legolas and never have two burdens. The moment I drew my narya, I allowed my sam to die. The deck was very good, but you saw the boy lacked some experience. His rohan riders were quickly (site 5 when I was on 7 or 8) swarmed.<br />
A cool situation during the game, he plays suddenly 5 easterlings (as I had to play Eomer right before going to site 7) so I had to exhaust my Aragorn to shoot some. Aragorn with a brand against an exhausted easterling lieutenant (8), he pumps it up and you see he’s glad to be rid of Aragorn, I play an affairs and keep him another turn on the table. I tell him that’s exactly how you can recognize a good deck, whatever you try to do, they always have an answer ready. My friend has lost and now he and I will be battling for second place. Luc will remain undefeated.<br />
<br />
Six: Lander Oosterlynck (1718)<br />
<br />
For some strange reasons he has more rating than me, he has the correct rating for his level, but I am a bit under my level. Well, I’m working on that. A friend of us has arrived and he will be observing the game. Lander tells him that as we play so often against each other, he knows my deck thoroughly. However, he remarks, that I know his deck too and that I can use that knowledge to a better end. He starts confident at the match, because after I made a few changes in his heavy denial deck and he has learned not to play his arwen against moria, he mostly wins against me. I played the day before a match against him, and lost on purpose to make him more confident. Normally I bid two, but now I bid 5 and start sam, with his 4 burdens and the rare pippin, suddenly he doesn’t look too confident anymore. He plays Nazgul and I want to begin, so I can avoid them a bit. I have a sword and a brand, but have to wait untill site 3 to play them. I stop at 2. He moves to 3. I catch up. He moves to four. I play nothing and set my hand up. But he smells something and stops. I move to 5, sacrificing one companion for the sake of the race. He moves to 6, I get some orcs on my swarm, but I have to sac two armories for it. With a bit of luck, I can kill at site 7. I move to 6, healing is important and I don’t have a dark places. I kill two companions but Frodo and Aragorn with bow stay alive. Again I need two armories to accomplish this. I play sting, look at his hand, sees two gandalf-kill cards and decide not to play gandalf. I move to 8, sac two companions, only having an exhausted aragorn and frodo, but I still have three companions in my hand. I hope he falls for it, but again he knows me too well. He says he can’t defeat me with his minions and moves to 8, after healing his exhausted aragorn with bow two times. I only have a runner, a scimitar and a troll in my hand, but I can’t play the troll, as all my armories are gone. I play nothing, my reconciliation is terrible. He goes to 9,  I know he has a paths (sting). But frodo is overwhelmed by the cave troll. All I need is enough minions to overwhelm Aragorn in his first skirmish. I don’t have much hope, I play the runner with his scimitar, draw a card, another scimitar, that was the reason why it was worth to get rid of my armories as they were doing nothing without scimitars. I remove two burdens and go fetch a scavengers with a scimitar. AND I DRAW A THEY ARE COMING! I say a curse word, put they are coming on the table, go get two minions and play my cave troll. Lander says I am a lucky bastard and makes some more rather personal remarks. But I win.<br />
<br />
I hope this wasn’t too long and that is was a bit worth reading. It’s my first report, but I think the tournament was interesting enough, to post it. If you are interested in participating, we have a group here on decktech.net (where the tournament director will post a report too)plus you can d-mail me if you’re interested.<br />
 <br></font></blockquote><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?id=4212&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
